title: JHTP11_07-4.pptx
summary: Java arrays are fixed-length, 0-indexed, homogeneous data, initialized with `new` or `{}`, pass-by-value; enhanced for iterates. Bounds are checked (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException). `java.util.Arrays` offers utilities. `ArrayLists` are dynamic, generic, resizable collections with `add`/`get`/`remove` methods, using `<>`.

title: JHTP11_08.pptx
summary: Chapter 8 delves into advanced Java classes: access control (public/private), constructors (overloading, `this` reference), exceptions, and composition. It details `enum` types, `static` and `final` members, packages, set/get methods with validation, and garbage collection. The chapter also covers `BigDecimal` for precise monetary calculations.

title: JHTP11_09.pptx
summary: Java inheritance creates subclasses from superclasses ("is-a" relationship) for code reuse, extending members and overriding methods. It's single-inheritance from Object. Constructors chain to superclass. While `protected` allows subclass access, `private` superclass variables with public accessors are preferred for robust, less coupled designs. Composition offers a flexible, loosely coupled alternative to inheritance.

title: JHTP11_10.pptx
summary: Polymorphism processes subclass objects via a superclass type, dynamically executing methods for system extensibility. Interfaces define common methods for unrelated classes, allowing polymorphic processing. Java 8+ added default, static, and private interface methods, enhancing flexibility and promoting loose coupling.

title: JHTP11_11.pptx
summary: Java exception handling uses `try-catch-finally` to manage runtime problems (e.g., `ArithmeticException`), allowing programs to continue. Exceptions inherit from `Throwable`; checked types require `catch`/`throws`, unchecked are `RuntimeException` subclasses. `finally` blocks and `try-with-resources` ensure resource deallocation. Custom/chained exceptions and assertions support robust error management.

Chapter_1_V7.01.pptx
summary: The Internet is a global network of interconnected devices and ISPs, governed by protocols, using packet switching in its core and various access networks at the edge. Performance is measured by delay, loss, and throughput. It employs a layered architecture, faces security challenges, and has evolved from ARPAnet to its current form.

title: Chapter_1-3_review.pptx
summary: The midterm covers Networking Ch. 1-3, focusing on Internet architecture, packet/circuit switching, app architectures (CS/P2P), HTTP, DNS, and TCP/UDP protocols (incl. flow/congestion control). It assesses concepts, protocols, and performance analysis (delay, throughput, rdt). The 50-min, closed-book exam has short answer, calculation, and design problems.

title: Chapter_1-6_review.pptx
summary: This final review summarizes networking concepts from physical to application layers, covering internet architecture, protocols (HTTP, TCP, IP, BGP), underlying mechanisms, and performance analysis. Topics include switching, routing, error detection, and signal modulation. The exam tests these via selection and calculation questions.

title: Chapter_2_V7.01.pptx
summary: The Application Layer examines network application architectures (client-server, P2P), transport services (TCP/UDP), and protocols like HTTP, DNS, and SMTP/POP3/IMAP. Topics include web caching, email, P2P file distribution (BitTorrent), video streaming with CDNs, and socket programming for app development, emphasizing distributed system design and scalability.

title: Chapter_3_V7.01.pptx
summary: The Transport Layer manages end-to-end communication, offering multiplexing/demultiplexing. UDP provides connectionless, best-effort service. TCP ensures reliable, ordered data transfer using sequence numbers, ACKs, timers, and pipelining (e.g., Go-Back-N/Selective Repeat). It incorporates flow control via receive windows and robust congestion control through AIMD (slow start, congestion avoidance, fast retransmit), established by a 3-way handshake.

title: Chapter_4_V7.01.pptx
summary: The Network Layer's data plane handles packet forwarding. It covers router architecture; IP (IPv4/IPv6 datagrams, fragmentation, addressing, NAT, tunneling); and generalized forwarding. This includes SDN/OpenFlow, using match+action rules for flexible packet handling via centralized control.

title: Chapter_5_V7.01.pptx
summary: Chapter 5 details network layer control planes: traditional routing (OSPF link-state, BGP inter-AS distance-vector); Software-Defined Networking (SDN) with OpenFlow, ODL/ONOS for centralized control; ICMP diagnostics; and SNMP network management.

title: Chapter_6_V7.01.pptx
summary: Chapter 6 details the Link Layer's role in datagram transfer between adjacent nodes, covering services like error detection/correction (CRC, parity) and medium access control (e.g., CSMA/CD, TDMA). It explores LANs, including MAC addressing, ARP, Ethernet frames, self-learning switches, and VLANs for network segmentation. Also introduced are MPLS for link virtualization, data center networking, and the journey of a web request through these layers.

title: CMPSC465_10_20_2025.pdf
summary: Greedy algorithms make local optimal choices, often fast but not always globally optimal (e.g., Knapsack). They yield optimal solutions given greedy choice and optimal substructure. Applications include Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) (e.g., Kruskal's algorithm), where they guarantee optimality.

title: CMPSC465_10_22_2025.pdf

It then introduces the Disjoint Set (Union-Find) data structure, essential for Kruskal's implementation, explaining its `Union` and `Find` operations, demonstrating a naive, inefficient approach, and presenting an optimized version to enhance performance.

title: CMPSC465_10_24_2025.pdf
summary: This content explores Disjoint Set Union (DSU) for managing non-overlapping sets, detailing `union` and `find` operations. It highlights optimizations like weighted-union and path compression, which improve time complexity from O(N) to O(logN) and amortized O(α(n)) respectively. DSU is applied to greedy algorithms such as Kruskal's for Minimum Spanning Trees and single-linkage clustering, demonstrated with examples in taxonomy.

Scalability is key, quantified by Big-O notation (f=O(g)) to describe growth rates, ignoring constants for large 'n'.

title: lec2.pdf
summary: Asymptotic notations describe function growth rates. Big-O (O) defines an upper bound where f(n) grows no faster than g(n). Big-Omega (Ω) sets a lower bound, meaning f(n) grows no slower than g(n). Big-Theta (Θ) signifies a tight bound, indicating f(n) and g(n) grow at the same asymptotic rate. Various facts and limit properties simplify their application.

title: lec3.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Lecture III by Ke Chen covers sorting algorithms, defining the problem and detailing two methods. InsertionSort (O(n^2) time, O(1) space) iteratively inserts elements into a partially sorted sequence. MergeSort (O(n log n) time, O(n) space) uses a divide-and-conquer strategy, recursively splitting arrays, sorting halves, and then merging them.

title: lec4.pdf
summary: This lecture details methods for solving recurrences like MergeSort's T(n)=2T(n/2)+O(n). Techniques include substitution (proving O(n log n) by induction), unrolling the recurrence to sum work, and using a recursion tree. These approaches lead to the Master Theorem, which provides a generalized solution for T(n)=aT(n/b)+O(n^d) based on constants a, b, and d.

title: lec5.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 covered MergeSort's O(n log n) time complexity, demonstrating its asymptotic optimality for comparison-based sorting using the Information Theory Lower Bound (ITLB). The ITLB, derived from decision tree analysis, establishes an Ω(n log n) lower bound for comparisons. The lecture also introduced QuickSort, a divide-and-conquer algorithm with O(n) partitioning, noting its O(n^2) worst-case time complexity.

title: lec6.pdf
summary: QuickSort uses O(N) partitioning for O(N log N) average, O(N^2) worst-case sorting. For selection, Randomized Selection is O(N) average, O(N^2) worst. The Median of Medians algorithm achieves deterministic O(N) worst-case selection by strategically picking pivots.

title: lec7.pdf
summary: This lecture explores Divide-and-Conquer algorithms. Median of Medians for selection achieves O(n) time by grouping elements to find a robust pivot. Matrix multiplication, typically O(n^3), can be improved by Strassen's algorithm to O(n^2.81) using 7 subproblems. Additionally, both the Closest Pair of Points and Convex Hull problems are solved efficiently with O(n log n) Divide-and-Conquer approaches.

title: lec8.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 LECTURE VIII introduces Binary Heaps after reviewing stacks and queues. Binary heaps are complete binary trees enforcing the max-heap property (parent >= children). This structure allows for O(1) GetMax and O(logn) insertion, where new elements are added to the end and then "HeapifyUp" (bubble up) to restore the heap property. Complete trees map efficiently to array representations.

title: lec9.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 LECTURE IX by Ke Chen introduces binary max-heaps as complete binary trees satisfying H[i] >= H[parent(i)], having O(log n) height. Heap operations like Insert, Delete, IncreaseKey, and DecreaseKey are all O(log n). HeapSort leverages max-heaps to sort an array in O(n log n) time and can be implemented in-place with O(1) space by first building the heap in O(n) time.

title: lec10.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 defines graphs as sets of vertices (nodes) and edges, distinguishing between undirected and directed types. Tracing back to Euler, graphs model various relationships and are stored using adjacency matrices or lists. The lecture introduces connected components and algorithms like DFS/BFS to find them, determining vertex connectivity.

title: lec11.pdf
summary: Depth First Search (DFS) on undirected graphs identifies connected components by recursively exploring vertices, using a `visited` array and stack for backtracking, assigning unique colors to each. It achieves optimal O(V+E) complexity with adjacency lists. DFS also detects cycles via back edges and collects pre/post-visit timestamps to gather more graph information.

title: lec12.pdf
summary: DFS on directed graphs employs pre/post-visit timestamps to distinguish tree, forward, back, and cross edges. Back edges uniquely identify cycles. Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAGs) permit topological sorting, an ordering where edges go from earlier to later vertices. This sort is efficiently achieved in O(V+E) by collecting nodes in decreasing post-visit time during DFS.

title: lec13.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 covers Strongly Connected Components (SCCs) in directed graphs, defined as vertex sets with bidirectional paths. The efficient O(|V|+|E|) algorithm utilizes two DFS traversals: first on the reverse graph (GR) to determine post-order numbers, then on the original graph (G), processing vertices in decreasing post-order to identify and extract each SCC.

title: lec14.pdf
summary: Explores Breadth First Search (BFS) for graph traversal and shortest paths. BFS uses a queue to explore graphs "layer by layer", effectively finding reachable vertices and single-source shortest paths in unweighted graphs with O(|V|+|E|) complexity. It introduces concepts for weighted graphs, including using dummy nodes for positive integer edge weights.

title: lec15.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 presents Dijkstra's Algorithm for shortest paths on weighted graphs (non-negative edges). It improves upon inefficient dummy node methods, iteratively selecting the unvisited vertex with the minimum path estimate ("alarm time"), updating neighbors, and confirming its path. A min-heap optimizes the O(|V|^2) naive implementation for faster vertex selection.

title: lec16.pdf
summary: Dijkstra's Algorithm, a weighted BFS, finds shortest paths from a source in graphs with positive edge weights. It uses a priority queue to iteratively extract the unvisited node with the minimum current distance, updating neighbor distances. Its binary min-heap complexity is O((|V|+|E|)log|V|), with ongoing research seeking optimization.

title: lec17.pdf
summary: Dijkstra's algorithm fails with negative edge weights or cycles, as shortest distances become undefined. The Bellman-Ford algorithm addresses this by iteratively relaxing all graph edges `|V|-1` times. This computes single-source shortest paths in `O(|V|*|E|)` time, detects negative cycles, and can be extended for `O(|V|^2*|E|)` all-pairs shortest path solutions.

title: lec18.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 (Oct 10, 2025) covers All Pairs Shortest Paths (APSP) using Floyd-Warshall (O(V^3), detects negative cycles) by recursively updating distances. It also defines Maximum Flow for capacitated directed graphs with source/sink, detailing s-t flows with capacity/conservation rules to find the highest value.

title: lec19.pdf
summary: The Maximum Flow Problem aims to find the highest value flow from a source to a sink in a directed graph, adhering to edge capacities and flow conservation. The Ford-Fulkerson algorithm solves this by iteratively finding augmenting paths in a residual graph, which contains forward edges with available capacity and backward edges to reverse existing flow, thereby increasing the total flow until no such path exists.

title: lec20.pdf
summary: The Ford-Fulkerson algorithm calculates max flow in a network by augmenting paths in residual graphs. While not polynomial in general, it proves the Max-Flow Min-Cut Theorem: max flow value equals min s-t cut capacity. This theorem has diverse applications in graph theory & optimization.

title: quiz_1_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 1 covered core Data Structures & Algorithms topics, including valid InsertionSort array transition states and clarifying that Big-O and Big-Omega denote upper/lower bounds, not inherently worst/best-case performance. Questions also assessed comparing function growth rates using O/Ω notation and fundamental properties of MergeSort, highlighting its divide-and-conquer nature where sorting occurs in the merge step.

title: quiz_1.pdf
summary: This document is Quiz 1 for CMPSC 465 Data Structures & Algorithms, Fall 2025. It features five multiple-choice questions covering core concepts: InsertionSort array transitions, Big-O and Big-Omega definitions for algorithm analysis, Big-O relationships between functions, Big-Omega proof by definition, and properties of MergeSort.

title: quiz_2_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 2 (Fall 2025) covered key data structures and algorithms: Master Theorem (requires Θ(n^d) vs O(2n·d)), median-of-medians' O(n) complexity, merge sort's sorted output, QuickSort's pivot for partitioning, and standard divide-and-conquer matrix multiplication's O(n^3) time.

title: quiz_2.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 Data Structures & Algorithms Quiz 2 (Fall 2025) covers Master Theorem applicability to recurrences, the time complexity of the median-of-medians algorithm, merge sort's merge operation, QuickSort's pivot role, and the time complexity of standard divide-and-conquer matrix multiplication.

title: quiz_3_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 3 covers heap fundamentals: In a min-heap, parent nodes are less than or equal to their children. Increasing a max-heap's root value does not violate the heap property. A binary heap of height 'h' must have a minimum of 2^h nodes. If HeapSort uses a min-heap, the array is sorted in descending order.

title: quiz_3.pdf
summary: Quiz 3 from CMPSC 465, Fall 2025, tests knowledge of heap properties. Topics include min/max-heap relationships, operations (IncreaseKey, Insert), minimum node count by height, and HeapSort behavior when using min-heaps.

title: quiz_4_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 4 covered data structures and algorithms, clarifying that verifying a single edge in an adjacency list takes O(n), identifying plausible DFS traversals, stating the maximum edges in a simple undirected graph is n(n-1)/2, confirming topological sort isn't always unique, and defining DFS back edges as leading to an ancestor node.

title: quiz_4.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Data Structures & Algorithms Quiz 4 (Fall 2025, Ke Chen & Yana Safonova) consists of 5 multiple-choice questions on graph theory. Topics include edge verification in adjacency lists, DFS traversals, max edges in simple undirected graphs, topological sort uniqueness in DAGs, and back edge definitions in DFS trees.

title: quiz_5_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 5 covers graph algorithms: In DFS, if an edge exists from SCC A to B, max post-number in A > max post-number in B. BFS always finds shortest paths in unweighted graphs. Dijkstra's algorithm fails with negative-weight edges, but when a vertex is visited, its distance is the true shortest path. Unique shortest paths are not guaranteed even with distinct edge weights.

title: quiz_5.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 Quiz 5 (Fall 2025) covers Data Structures & Algorithms topics including strongly connected components and `post` numbers, BFS for shortest paths in unweighted graphs, Dijkstra's algorithm limitations (negative-weight edges) and behavior upon visiting a node, and the uniqueness of shortest paths in weighted graphs.

title: quiz_6_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Quiz 6 covered algorithms: Bellman-Ford fails on undirected graphs with negative edge cycles; over-updating is harmless without negative cycles. Floyd-Warshall's recursion is `min(dist k-1[i,j], dist k-1[i,k]+dist k-1[k,j])`. Network flow: source output equals sink input, and increasing edge capacity doesn't always boost max flow.

title: quiz_6.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Fall 2025 Quiz 6, from Ke Chen & Yana Safonova, assessed students on data structures and algorithms. Questions covered Bellman-Ford's use with negative edge weights and iteration effects, Floyd-Warshall's recursion, and network flow properties including valid flow definitions and how maximum flow reacts to capacity increases.

title: rec_7_solution.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 worksheet solution covers Max Flow Min Cut using Ford-Fulkerson, including residual graph construction. It details reducing multi-source/multi-sink max-flow problems and employee-project assignment to standard max-flow instances. Additionally, a linear-time algorithm is presented for verifying a max-flow solution by checking for an s-t path in the residual graph via BFS.

title: recitation_3_sol.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Worksheet 3 explains min-heap delete-min (root swap, heapify-down) and max-heap building (iterative heapify-down). It proves a max node count at height h and details an O(nlogk) time/O(k) space min-heap algorithm for finding the k-th largest element.

title: recitation_3.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Worksheet 3 details min-heap delete-min (replace root, heapify-down) and max-heap Build-heap (Max-Heapify-Down from n/2). Proof shows an n-element heap has at most ⌈n/2^(h+1)⌉ nodes at height h. The k-th largest element is found via a size-k min-heap in O(n log k) time and O(k) space.

title: recitation_4_sol.pdf
summary: This worksheet covers graph algorithms, detailing DFS for traversal, pre/post-visits, and edge classification. Solutions include linear-time algorithms for awardee lineup via topological sort, bipartite graph detection using two-coloring DFS, water pouring puzzle pathfinding, constant-time ancestor queries using pre/post-visit times, and calculating max descendant values in trees.

title: recitation_4.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Wk 4 covers graph/tree algorithms: DFS (traversal, numbering, edge types), topological sort for scheduling (O(m+n)), bipartite graph detection (O(|V|+|E|)), graph modeling for state-space problems (pouring water), plus tree problems: constant-time ancestor queries (linear preproc), and linear-time max descendant value calculation.

title: recitation_5_sol.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 worksheet covers graph algorithms: Strongly Connected Components (SCC) analysis for connectivity/minimum edges, and shortest path variations. It details multi-source BFS, and Dijkstra's adapted for edge budget, max edge weight, or a required intermediate node.

title: recitation_5.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Worksheet 5 focuses on graph algorithms, covering Strongly Connected Components (SCC) analysis including pre/post numbers, component ordering, and metagraphs, plus determining minimum edges for strong connectivity. It also features Dijkstra's algorithm modifications for multi-source shortest paths, paths with edge budget limits, maximum edge weight constraints, and all-pairs shortest paths through a pinned node.

title: recitation_6_sol.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 worksheet demonstrates Dijkstra's, Bellman-Ford, and Floyd-Warshall shortest path algorithms with step-by-step solutions. It critiques a proposed method for Dijkstra's with negative edges using a counterexample. The content also covers network flow, including validating a flow, identifying bottleneck edges, and providing an example of a network without them.

title: recitation_6.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Worksheet 6 covers shortest path algorithms: Dijkstra's (including validity with negative edges by constant shift), Bellman-Ford, and Floyd-Warshall. It also explores network flow, specifically validating flow functions and identifying bottleneck edges in maximum flow networks.

title: recitation_8.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Worksheet 8 focuses on Minimum Spanning Trees. Tasks include applying Prim's algorithm, analyzing MSTs in subgraphs, and determining impacts of edge weight increments on MSTs and shortest paths. It also requires modifying Kruskal's for specific edges and transforming graphs to handle negative weights for MST computation.

title: recitation1_sol.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 465 worksheet covers asymptotic analysis. It includes ordering functions by growth rates (constant to exponential), analyzing pseudo-code running times (e.g., Θ(n^2), Θ(n log log n)), proving summation identities (e.g., ∑k^j=Θ(n^(j+1)), ∑∑ij=Θ(n^4)), and solving recurrence relations (e.g., O(n^4 log n), O(n^(3/2)log n), O(n^(2/3))).

title: recitation1.pdf
summary: CMPSC 465 Fall 2025 Worksheet 1, dated Sep 8, 2025, covers four key areas: comparing functions by asymptotic growth, analyzing pseudo-code running times using Θ-notation, proving summation identities, and solving recurrence relations to find tight upper bounds (O-notation).

title: recitation2_sol.pdf
summary: Worksheet 2 details algorithms: k-th smallest in O(log(m+n)); matrix max O(n^2) using D&C; selection (groups of 7) is O(n); median via O(1) calls to a specialized (n/10)-th smallest finder; k-way merge in O(nk log k); and finding array rotations in O(log n).

title: CMPSC461-Python.pdf
summary: This course features two Python projects, assuming prior programming knowledge. Resources are provided for Python review (syntax, data structures, debugging), with one month to prepare. Instructors will offer conceptual and design guidance, but students must debug their own code as direct code fixes will not be provided for this 400-level course.

title: Exception.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461's 'Exceptions' addresses program deviations (e.g., out-of-memory, divide-by-zero). While C uses workarounds like special return values, modern languages provide features to isolate error-checking and direct execution to handlers. Exceptions are pre-defined or user-defined, generated via 'throw', caught, and involve propagation.

title: Finite-Automata-Annotated.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461 explores implementing regular expressions (REs) via finite automata. REs are equivalent to NFAs and DFAs. Implementation involves converting REs to NFAs, then either simulating the NFA directly or converting it to a DFA for simulation. This process forms the basis of lexical analysis, addressing token ambiguities through principles like longest matching prefix and token priority.

title: Finite-Automata.pdf
summary: Finite Automata (NFAs/DFAs) are equivalent to regular expressions, implementing them via NFA simulation or NFA-to-DFA conversion and simulation. For lexical analysis, token NFAs are combined, resolving ambiguities using longest prefix and priority rules, often by merging all NFAs into a single automaton.

title: flashcards.txt
summary: Lexical analysis divides character streams into tokens (lexemes, e.g., identifiers, operators) by matching patterns typically defined by regular expressions. Key regex concepts include finite alphabets, the null string (ε), backslash for escaping, and precedence (closure > concatenation > alternation). Unrecognized tokens trigger lexical error recovery.

title: Functional-Programming(Conditions_Functions)-Annotated.pdf
summary: This CMPSC 461 material covers Functional Programming concepts in Scheme, detailing boolean values and predicates, conditional expressions (`if`, `cond`), and mutual recursion. It introduces higher-order functions, which accept or return functions, and explains local binding constructs like `let` (simultaneous), `let*` (sequential), and `letrec` (recursive definitions).

title: Functional-Programming(Conditions_Functions).pdf
summary: Scheme FP covers booleans (#t/#f), predicates, operators, and `if`/`cond` conditionals. It introduces mutual recursion and Higher-Order Functions (first-class). Variable binding uses `let` (simultaneous), `let*` (sequential), and `letrec` (recursive) constructs.

title: Functional-Programming(Lists-More).pdf
summary: CMPSC 461 with Prof. Suman Saha introduces Functional Programming List concepts, including defining a `subs` function to replace list elements, computing list sum/product without higher-order functions, and detailing `foldl` (left-associative function application) and `foldr` (right-associative function application).

title: Functional-Programming(Lists)-Annotated.pdf
summary: This Scheme Functional Programming content covers lists, explaining quoting for data and core operations: `null?`, `car`, `cdr`, `cons`. It details recursive list ops like `length`, `append`, `member?`, `map` (function application), `reduce` (cumulative reduction), and introduces association lists for key-value binding/lookup.

title: Functional-Programming(Lists).pdf
summary: Scheme's functional programming uses lists as nested data structures. Quoting (`'`) treats expressions as data. Core operations (`car`, `cdr`, `cons`, `null?`) manipulate lists. Advanced functions like `map` and `reduce` enable complex list processing. Association lists provide key-value mapping via `bind` and `lookup`.

title: Functional-Programming(Variable_Expression_Functions)-Annotated.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461 introduces Functional Programming using Scheme, taught by Suman Saha. Scheme, influencing modern languages, employs recursion, prefix expressions (e.g., (+ 3 4)), dynamic typing, and treats functions as values. It utilizes DrRacket, features user-defined and anonymous functions, `define` for variables, and lists as its primary data structure.

title: Functional-Programming(Variable_Expression_Functions).pdf
summary: CMPSC 461 by Suman Saha introduces Functional Programming via Scheme, a paradigm distinct from imperative languages. Scheme uses DrRacket, employs prefix notation for expressions, dynamic typing, and treats functions as values (lambda functions, recursion), influencing modern multi-paradigm languages like Python and Java.

title: Functions.pdf
summary: Functions (subroutines/methods) can be value-returning or not, using formal parameters and actual arguments. Inline expansion optimizes calls by replacing them with code. Parameter passing mechanisms include Call by Value (copy-in), Call by Result (copy-out), Call by Value-Result (copy-in/out), Call by Reference (address/alias), and Call by Name (textual substitution), influencing how data is shared and modified between caller and callee.

title: Grammar-Annotated.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461's grammar unit covers syntax analysis, interpreting tokens via Context-Free Grammars (CFGs). Developed by Chomsky and described in BNF/EBNF, CFGs use production rules to define language syntax, enabling string derivations (e.g., leftmost/rightmost). They are more powerful than regular expressions for programming language structures like balanced parentheses, defining the language L(G) for valid strings.

title: Grammar.pdf
summary: Syntax analysis interprets tokens to recover program structure. Regular languages are insufficient for this, necessitating Context-Free Grammars (CFGs) using BNF/EBNF. CFGs define languages through derivations; all regular languages are context-free. Designing CFGs involves recursive thinking to generate all correct strings and no incorrect ones.

title: grammar.txt
summary: This BNF defines an imperative language with sequential statements: assignment, if/else, for loops, and print. Expressions support arithmetic (+-*/%), comparisons (==, !=, <, >), and boolean logic (AND, OR, NOT). Identifiers and numbers serve as primary elements, with nested boolean expressions also supported.

title: Introduction.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461 (Programming Language Concepts) with Prof. Suman Saha explores language principles, paradigms (Imperative, Functional, OOP), syntax, semantics, and implementation. Grading: 20% Assignments, 10% Projects, 40% Midterms, 30% Final Exam. Communications via Campuswire/Canvas. Strict academic integrity, mandatory AI quiz.

title: Lambda-Calculus-Boolean.pdf
summary: Suman Saha's CMPSC 461 material introduces λ-Calculus Boolean concepts, covering bound versus free variables (with examples), useful rules, evaluation, evaluation order, β-reduction (with examples), and the encoding of Boolean values within λ-Calculus.

title: Lambda-Calculus.pdf
summary: Prof. Suman Saha's CMPSC 461 explores λ-Calculus, detailing its syntax, application to programming languages, and anonymous functions. It covers λ-term examples, syntax vs. semantics, capture-avoiding substitution, bound/free variables, and α-reduction, concluding with β-reduction, including formal definitions and examples.

title: Lexical-Analysis.pdf
summary: Lexical Analysis, the compiler's front-end, converts a source character stream into a token stream for syntax analysis. It identifies meaningful lexemes, labeling them with tokens defined by patterns (regular expressions), while removing non-significant elements. Key challenges involve lookahead and error recovery.

title: Memory-Management.pdf
summary: Professor Suman Saha's CMPSC 461, Programming Language Concepts, covers Memory Management. Topics include heap management and various garbage collection techniques: reference counting, tracing collection methods like Mark-And-Sweep, Mark-and-Compact, and Stop-and-Copy (Stop-the-World collectors), plus Short-Pause and Generational GC.

title: Names-Bindings-Scopes.pdf
summary: Semantic analysis validates programs, ensuring name, type, and declaration correctness by handling non-context-free syntax errors. Names bind to objects, with lifetimes determined by static, stack, or heap allocation. Lexical/static scopes (managed by symbol tables) define name visibility. Binding (shallow/deep) for function parameters and stack frames (using static/dynamic links) implement these scoping rules.

title: note-1.pdf
summary: Lambda calculus is a system describing functions via variables, application, and abstraction (λx:t). It defines free/bound variables, lexical scope, and first-class functions. Core operations are capture-avoiding substitution and reductions: α (renaming), β (function application: (λx:t)t0 = t[t0/x]), and η (simplification: λx:tx = t). Classical LC permits non-deterministic reduction order.

title: note-2.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461's Lecture Note 2 details encoding booleans and integers within lambda calculus. Booleans `TRUE` (`xy:x`) and `FALSE` (`xy:y`) are defined, along with `IF` and `AND` functions. Integers are represented by Church numerals (`n = f z:f^n z`), and functions like `SUCC`, `PLUS`, and `MULT` are constructed from the core calculus to enable arithmetic.

title: Parsing.pdf
summary: CMPSC 461's parsing unit examines parse trees as graphical derivations, detailing their root (start symbol), internal nodes (RHS grammar), and terminal leaves. It addresses grammar ambiguity—when a string has multiple parse trees—and its resolution through precedence, associativity, and grammar rewriting. The content introduces Abstract Syntax Trees (ASTs) as simplified parse trees, and differentiates between top-down and bottom-up parsing techniques.

title: tokens.txt
summary: This content defines tokens for a grammar used in checker.py, encompassing programming language elements like identifiers, numbers, keywords (IF, FOR, PRINT), logical (AND, OR, NOT), arithmetic (+, -, *, /, %), and comparison (==, !=, <, >) operators, assignment (=), plus punctuation ((), ,, :) and EOF.

title: Types.pdf
summary: Types are collections of values sharing structural properties and operations, crucial for program organization, optimization, and preventing type errors where operations are undefined for a given data type. Type systems impose constraints, categorized as static (compile-time checking) or dynamic (run-time checking), with tradeoffs in flexibility and performance. Languages are also classified as strongly or weakly typed based on error detection. Type systems define rules for equivalence (name vs. structural), compatibility, and inference.
